Introduction

The environmental conditions play a crucial role in the evolution of species. Hence, through time, natural populations tend to diversify in different geographical landscapes (Raeymaekers et al. 2017). Otherwise, if the rate of adaptability is low, then the danger of species extinction rises (Kemppainen et al. 2021). Adapting to environmental changes requires either novel mutations or heritable variation, with the latter being the fastest way to adapt to the local environment (Kemppainen et al. 2021). Populations sharing the same genetic pool of alleles may develop similar forms (parallel evolution), when exposed to analogous environmental conditions, provided that there are no founder events or random genetic drift. In the latter cases, even if advantageous genetic variants occur, they can be lost due to the reduced likelihood of the variants to mate with the local population. Thus, in case  these events should occur, adaptation remains unlikely (Kemppainen et al. 2021). 

In order to better understand geographically-based biodiversity patterns it is important to quantify the variability of evolutionary potential (Raeymaekers et al. 2017). It has been observed, through the use of genomic tools, that species living in common landscapes may have different evolutionary potential (Raeymaekers et al. 2017).

Local adaptation is the process according to which, certain beneficial traits are present in the local population and lead to better adaptation to the local environmental conditions (eg. higher survival and reproduction chances) (Meek et al. 2023).

Adaptive divergence is the process where new species variations arise from a shared common ancestor due to their ability to adapt to different environmental conditions. By adapting to different environmental conditions, populations can become genetically and phenotypically distinct from each other. This eventually leads to the development of new subpopulations and potentially species (Tusso et al. 2021)

The ability of three spined stickleback to gradually colonize and adapt to freshwater lakes and streams from the ocean is based on epigenetic modifications that  have contributed to parallel evolution of the species. Specifically, comparing three spined sticklebacks individuals that inhabit freshwater and brackish water, Hu (et al. 2022) observed methylation differences depending on the type of water (freshwater vs brackish). Moreover, Hu et al. 2022 found that when ancestral marine fish migrate to freshwater environments, they present a greater number of methylated CpG sites which remain heritable, whereas the transition of freshwater ecotypes back to the marine environment (with increased salinity) present non-heritable changes. Hence, the latter population presents plasticity. Furthermore, when three spined stickleback individuals were challenged with different salinity environments, due to colonization, plastic responses were more frequently reported rather than heritable changes. This phenomenon presents the direction of divergence in three spined sticklebacks regarding water salinity (Hu et al. 2022).

Research questions

  • Do habitat conditions affect body weight?

  • Do habitat conditions affect body length?

  • Are there in site variations in the same habitat for body weight? What about body length?

  • Do habitat conditions affect each sex differently?

  • Do the environmental parameters (eg.mean temperature ) affect body weight and body length based on each habitat?

Methods

Fish species:

The dataset is part of the Raeymaekers et al. (2017). The dataset contains 192 samples from (Gasterosteus Aculeatus Linnaeus, 1758)  individuals (three-spined stickleback) that have been isolated from various coastal lowland sites in Belgium and Netherlands. There are eight populations from brackish and freshwater habitats. Individuals that belong to the brackish water habitat have been isolated from the L01, L02, L03, L05 sites whereas those that belong to the freshwater habitat have been isolated from the L07, L09, L10, L12 sites. From each site approximately 24 individuals have been sequenced using whole genome sequencing. The produced data were organized based on the chromosomes of each individual. The reference genome that was used in the analysis was downloaded from the Stickleback genome browser site (https://stickleback.genetics.uga.edu/) and the file used was threespine stickleback genome assembly v. 5.

Bioinformatics:

Monomorphic SNPs have been filtered to exclude all sites at which no alternative alleles are called for any of the samples and all sites at which only alternative alleles are called (all samples differ from the reference genome). Furthermore, multiallelic and low allele frequency (AF < 0.01) SNPs have also been removed.

An analysis pipeline was created in order to conduct a population genomic analysis using the above dataset. In the present analysis, chromosome X was used. Hence, the first step was to isolate chromosome X from the rest of the dataset using GNU/Linux commands. Afterwards, the R package vcfR was used for the visualization of the raw VCF data. Variants in raw VCF files were then subjected to extensive filtering based on the quality scores to reduce the number of low-quality SNPs.

Chromosome plots were produced using the vcfR package and chromoqc function in R (version 4.2.2) from Knaus et al. (2017). The next step was to convert the ploidy of genotypes into binary code using the library adagenet. In order to graphically assess the position of the polymorphic sites within a scaffold the snpposi.plot function was used. For the calculation of F-st, p values and bootstraps the StAMPP package was used. Next, the visualization of the genetic differentiation in an unrooted tree using the ape library package was performed. Succeeding this step, as a way of estimating the heterozygosity for each population the adegenet package was used. Last but not least, in order to explain the variation in our data Principal component analysis (PCA) was conducted.

Body length ~ habitat

Mean and median of body length

#Calculate mean body length for each habitat
mean_body_length_brackish <- mean(SampleInfo$Length.cm.[SampleInfo$Site %in% c("L01","L02","L03","L05")])
mean_body_length_Fresh <- mean(SampleInfo$Length.cm.[SampleInfo$Site %in% c("L07","L09","L10","L12")])

#Calculate the median body length for each habitat
median_body_length_brackish <- median(SampleInfo$Length.cm.[SampleInfo$Site %in% c("L01","L02","L03","L05")], na.rm = TRUE)
median_body_length_fresh <- median(SampleInfo$Length.cm.[SampleInfo$Site %in% c("L07","L09","L10","L12")], na.rm = TRUE)

Body length graph

#Visualize into a boxplot for length in cm
brackish_length <-SampleInfo$Length.cm.[SampleInfo$Site %in% c("L01","L02","L03","L05")]
fresh_length  <- SampleInfo$Length.cm.[SampleInfo$Site %in% c("L07","L09","L10","L12")]

#create a dataframe with the group labels and data. 
data <- data.frame(
  Group= factor(c(rep("brackish water",length(brackish_length)),rep("freshwater",length(fresh_length)))),
  Value= c(brackish_length,fresh_length)
)

#ggplot2
ggplot(data,aes(x=Group,y=Value)) + geom_boxplot() + ylab("length") + xlab("Group")

the graphs show the mean, median and the outliers for body length according to each habitat. From the graphs no visible differences can be seen when comparing body length vs habitat. Hence, the Wilcoxon test was performed, in order to assess if habitat conditions are statistically significant to affect the length of three-spined stickleback.

resultL <- wilcox.test(brackish_length, fresh_length)
print(resultL)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  brackish_length and fresh_length
## W = 3801, p-value = 0.03593
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

The p-value is smaller than 0.05 (p-value=0.03593), thus the result is statistically significant.

Body weight graph

groups <- c("brackish","fresh")
brackishW <- c(SampleInfo$Body_weight.g.[SampleInfo$Site %in% c("L01", "L02", "L03", "L05")])
freshW <- c(SampleInfo$Body_weight.g.[SampleInfo$Site %in% c("L07", "L09", "L10", "L012")])

  geom_boxplot() +

## Warning: Removed 1 rows containing non-finite values (`stat_boxplot()`).

Wilcoxon test was performed, in order to assess if habitat conditions are statistically significant to affect the body weight of three-spined stickleback.

resultW <- wilcox.test(brackishW, freshW)
print(resultW)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  brackishW and freshW
## W = 3750, p-value = 0.2869
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

The p-value is larger than 0.05 (p-value=0.2869), thus accepting the null-hypothesis which states there are no statistically significant differences between bodyweight and habitat

Wilcoxon test

Wilcoxon test was performed in order to test the hypothesis whether there are statistically significant differences between body length and sex.

#Compare female mean length in brackish and freshwater using the Wilcoxon rank sum exact test

mean_length_female_brackish <- mean(SampleInfo$Length.cm.[SampleInfo$Site %in% c("L01","L02","L03","L05") & SampleInfo$Sex == "F"])
mean_length_female_fresh <- mean(SampleInfo$Length.cm.[SampleInfo$Site %in% c("L07","L09","L10","L12") & SampleInfo$Sex == "F"])


#Compare male mean length

mean_length_male_brackish <- mean(SampleInfo$Length.cm.[SampleInfo$Site %in% c("L01","L02","L03","L05") & SampleInfo$Sex == "M"])
mean_length_male_fresh <-  mean(SampleInfo$Length.cm.[SampleInfo$Site %in% c("L07","L09","L10","L12") & SampleInfo$Sex == "M"])
# Wilcox test comparison between males (M) vs habitat (H) and females (F) Vs habitat (H)
resultHM <- wilcox.test(mean_length_male_brackish, mean_length_male_fresh)
resultHM 
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum exact test
## 
## data:  mean_length_male_brackish and mean_length_male_fresh
## W = 0, p-value = 1
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
resultHF <- wilcox.test(mean_length_female_brackish, mean_length_female_fresh)
resultHF
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum exact test
## 
## data:  mean_length_female_brackish and mean_length_female_fresh
## W = 0, p-value = 1
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
# Wilcox test comparison between males (M) vs females (F) in two different habitats (B= Brackish, F=Freshwater)

resultFM_B <- wilcox.test(mean_length_male_brackish, mean_length_female_brackish)
resultFM_B 
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum exact test
## 
## data:  mean_length_male_brackish and mean_length_female_brackish
## W = 0, p-value = 1
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
resultFM_F <- wilcox.test(mean_length_male_fresh, mean_length_female_fresh)
resultFM_F
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum exact test
## 
## data:  mean_length_male_fresh and mean_length_female_fresh
## W = 0, p-value = 1
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

All four Wilcox tests state the same result of p-value=1 which means that there are no statistically significant differences between sex and habitat. Hence, for this experiment the data show that each sex’s body length is not affected differently for each habitat (Brackish or Freshwater).

From the wilcox test, the p-value is equal to 1, which means that there are no statistically significant differences.

Do environmental parameters (eg mean temperature) affect body weight and body length based on each habitat or site?

According to the supplementary tables of the manuscript, there are variables like distance from the shore (in km), salinity, depth (cm) and pH values. Data for the mean temperature across the four seasons (spring 2008, fall 2008, spring 2009 and summer 2009) is not available.

I managed to find some information regarding the mean temperature across the four seasons that the experiment took place. I used the aquastat tool from fao.org.

Hence, we can compare the impact of mean temperature on body length and body weight.I compared bodyweight and bodylength of three spined individuals for the seasons:

  1. Spring 2008 vs Spring 2009

  2. Fall 2008 vs Summer 2009

Results

After the analysis of 192 Gasterosteus Aculeatus individuals, a comparison between the genome of the 192 individuals and that of the reference genome was conducted. Moreover, the differences between the populations of two different habitats were compared.

  1. The number of SNPs in chromosome X were calculated to be 148920 according to the reference genome.

  2. There are no statistically significant differences in body length/weight between habitats, although from our data, individuals from the brackish habitat seem to be bit heavier.

  3. All p-values from Fst are very close to 0 meaning that they are statistically significant. Moreover, the Fst values tend to be less than 0.15. Hence, the three-spined stickleback individuals are not statistically different. The L10 population from the brackish water habitat seems to be a little different compared to other population, yet because the F-st values are so low, no statistically significant result is produced.

  4. Heterozygosity appears to be pretty uniform across all populations, with population L10 displaying a bit lower heterozygosity in comparison to the rest of the populations.

  5. Brackish water populations (L01,L02,L03,L05) cluster together in a very compact form while 3 out of the 4 freshwater populations (L07,L09,L12) cluster more loosely together, with the L07 population clustering closer to the brackish water populations rather than the freshwater ones.

  6. Habitat conditions (brackish vs freshwater) do not affect the body weight or the body length of individuals at a different rate based on sex (males-females).

  7. There appears to be no correlation between the body weight/ body length and the mean temperature. Additionally, comparing body length for spring 2008 vs spring 2009 and fall 2008 vs summer 2009 did not change the result significantly. Nevertheless, there appears to be a tendency for individuals from the brackish habitat to be a little heavier in the spring 2008 vs spring 2009 comparison.
